The goal of generalized Born theory can be thought of as an effort to

find a relatively simple analytical formula resembling equation 25 that for

real molecular geometries will capture as much as possible the physics of

the Poisson equation. Hence, to obtain a formula such as equation 24, we

seek a function fGB, such that in the self terms (the first summation in

equation 25), fGB acts as an ‘‘effective Born radius’’ while in the pairwise

terms (second summation in equation 25) it becomes an effective

interaction distance. A variety of functional forms for fGB have been

tested (Onufriev et al., 2002), but the most common form chosen is (Still

et al., 1990):

